{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508857"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:09:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:09:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11355"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11355","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11355"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.04,0.82,0.01,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4000"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79124"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4000","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4000"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11355"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64476"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"476"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1254"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"12449"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3970"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4122"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5866"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5867"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27013"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79124","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79124"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 18-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner with a one-week history of fatigue, malaise, and sore throat. He denies recent travel, intravenous drug use, or exposure to sick contacts. On examination, his pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 120/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 19/min, and temperature is 38.5\u00b0C. His chest is clear on auscultation. Exudates are present on both tonsils. Cervical lymphadenopathy is present bilaterally. There is fullness and mild tenderness in the left upper quadrant of his abdomen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Group A streptococcus","Cytomegalovirus","Epstein-Barr virus","HIV seroconversion illness","Toxoplasmosis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a one-week history of \u003Cstrong\u003Efever, pharyngitis, and lymphadenopathy\u003C/strong\u003E which is the classic triad of \u003Cstrong\u003Einfectious mononucleosis (IM)\u003C/strong\u003E. While there are numerous causes (i.e., Group A Strep and CMV) of IM, the clinical syndrome is most commonly (~75%) associated with an Epstein-Barr virus (HHV-4) infection. Furthermore, splenomegaly favors the diagnosis of EBV-associated IM, as GAS is not a well-documented cause of splenomegaly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients with suspected IM based upon the clinical picture (history and exam) should have a white blood cell count with differential and a heterophile test or EBV serology (IgM \u0026amp; IgG) serology ordered. \u003Cstrong\u003EIgM \u0026amp; IgG antibodies for EBV\u003C/strong\u003E become detectable around the time of symptom onset due to the prolonged incubation period (i.e., 4-8 weeks). IgM-EBV antibodies are a marker of acute infection and disappear after approximately three months, the IgG antibodies remain for life and are a marker of prior EBV infection. IgM and IgG antibodies for the EBV capsid antigen have a sensitivity and specificity of 97% and 94%, respectively.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EMuch debate exists around the use of the heterophile antibody test (Monospot test) and EBV serology as both can be used to diagnose acute EBV infections. Both tests have high sensitivity and specificity and are still used, however, the Monospot test is available by point-of-care testing in some centers. Some providers prefer to use the EBV serology as it provides information about acute and past EBV infections, and if the only IgG is elevated it virtually excludes the diagnosis of acute EBV infection.\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESpecial attention should be given to \u003Cstrong\u003EGroup A streptococcus (i.e., \u003Cem\u003Estrep pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E)\u003C/strong\u003E in the diagnosis of EBV, particularly in at-risk populations like Aboriginal people and Torres Strait Islander people to help prevent rheumatic fever. EBV and GAS pharyngitis present as similar syndromes and can be difficult to distinguish clinically. One tool is the CENTOR criteria (McIsaac criteria) which calculates the probability of GAS infection (i.e., cough absent, tonsillar exudate, anterior cervical lymphadenopathy, fever, and age 3-14 years). Diagnosis of GAS pharyngitis is confirmed via throat culture for group A streptococcus is positive and may benefit from a course of antibiotic treatment. With this in mind, antibiotic therapy for GAS pharyngitis may be indicated presumptively in situations where there is a high epidemiological risk (e.g. among Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander populations) or where the diagnosis is confirmed with a throat culture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther answers:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECytomegalovirus: \u003C/strong\u003ETypical clinical picture of EBV with lymphadenopathy and splenomegaly. The Monospot test is negative for heterophile antibodies and CMV serology confirms the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHIV seroconversion illness: \u003C/strong\u003EMay present with fever, sore throat, and lymphadenopathy, but typically includes a rash and is confirmed with HIV serology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EToxoplasmosis:\u003C/strong\u003E Can cause lymphadenopathy and fever, but is less common and usually associated with exposure to cat feces or undercooked meat. Diagnosis is confirmed with serology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Infectious mononucleosis can be diagnosed with a combination of clinical features, blood examination, Monospot test, or EBV serology.","Epstein-Barr virus is the most common cause of infectious mononucleosis, especially in young adults.","Splenomegaly is a common finding in Epstein-Barr virus infection."],"references":["Dunmire SK, Hogquist KA, Balfour HH. Infectious Mononucleosis. Curr Top Microbiol Immunol. 2015;390(Pt 1):211-40. doi: 10.1007/978-3-319-22822-8_9. PMID: 26424648; PMCID: PMC4670567. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26424648/","Aronson, M., Auwaerter, P., Infectious mononucleosis [Internet] www.uptodate.com 2021 [cited 19 Sep 2021]. Available from https://www.uptodate.com/contents/infectious-mononucleosis","Electronic Therapeutic Guidelines. 2021. Epstein\u2013Barr virus (EBV) infection. [online] [Accessed 19 September 2021] Available from: https://tgldcdp-tg-org-au.ezproxy.flinders.edu.au/viewTopic?topicfile=epstein-barr-virus\u0026guidelineName=Antibiotic#toc_d1e47","Leung AKC, Lam JM, Barankin B. Infectious Mononucleosis: An Updated Review. Curr Pediatr Rev. 2024;20(3):305-322. doi: 10.2174/1573396320666230801091558. PMID: 37526456. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37526456/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64476"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11355"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64476","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64476"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T15:19:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T15:20:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4000"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79124"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"creat